Visualization Assignment 2 - Movie Ratings¶

Working with Lorraine's Movie Ratings data, Here's what we know so far:

This assignment uses data obtained via MovieLens. The data sets were collected by the GroupLens Research Project at the University of Minnesota.

This data set consists of:

  • 100,000 ratings (1-5) from 943 users on 1682 movies.
  • Each user has rated at least 20 movies.
  • Simple demographic info for the users (age, gender, occupation, zip)

The data was collected through the MovieLens web site (movielens.umn.edu) during the seven-month period from September 19th, 1997 through April 22nd, 1998.

What is this data telling us?

We have almost a thousand different movie raters, thousands of movies which each occupy 1 or more genres, and demographic and location data on the raters.

Some ideas of what we can explore through this data:¶

  • Which genres get the highest ratings, which get the lowest
  • Which occupations, age and location correlate with higher preference of genre
  • How genres and rating preferences change over time
  • How the time interval between interview date and movie release date affects the rating

We will break this analysis down by item of exploration. Each item with include a comprehansive visualization of the data, and a following statistical analysis to determine variable correlation, population parameters, and general indicators that will provide insight into the relationships between data variables and what those relationships could mean.

Lets perform a few descriptive analyses on the whole ataset to get a feel of what it's telling us, and then dive into the visualizations and statistical processes¶

What's the problem here? Well there are many problems. To start off, if we have too many categories, our box plot is just going to look crappy, as it does here. No one wants to read through all those Occupation names, and the boxes are smooshed together too tightly.

There's a bigger issue here though. Our Rating data is discrete and narrow (between 1 and 5), so all of our box plots will probably be the same dimension. Maybe one or two will be above or below another box plot. But they will almost always have the median, the IQ range will always be the same, and there will always be outlier poitns at y=1. Our box plot is also doing something interesting where it looks like boxes are overlaid on top of each other? I don't know anyting about this. Maybe the plot doesn't have enough space. Maybe the IQ range is actually larger on those data points. That explanation could make sense because as we can see, most of these boxes don't have their median outlined by the bar (remember the mean is around 3.5?). Perhaps as a result of our narrow ratings options, box plots just can't adequately plot against it.

What Age Correlates with Movie Preference, Ratings¶

In [146]:
reg = sns.regplot(x= 'Rating', y= 'Age', data= MovieRatings)
plt.title('Age Regressed Against Rating', size=30);

Like most of the plots thus far, it looks awkward. But it tells us something a little interesting: there seems to be a slight trend toward higher age associated with higher movie ratings. Although the trend is weak, this is the sort of finding that we're looking for from a visualization. This visualization could suggest to us that we want to model a linear regression against the data to prove or disprove that age is correlated with higher movie ratings.

Well this just looks overwhelming, but hey I can always use this method in the future, probably with a smaller dataset.

So what can we take away from our box plots? Let's looks at the box plot above WITHOUT the jitter to avoid getting a headache. It appears that the median and IQ range of age goes up as ratings go up, and down as ratings goes down. This reflects the regression line that we saw previously over our data, suggesting that higher age and higher ratings are positively correlated. One thing I don't like about these box plots is that it is not ordered by Rating. In fact, I don't even know what it is ordered by. This is something I should look into for future plots that I make.

Summarizing Our Findings¶

Here are my takeaways so far from visualizing this dataset in various contexts:

  • The survey itself may be biased, because there are twice as many men than there are women who are respondants
  • We know the counts of each genre (drama being the highest), which may reflect the reality of what proportion of genres are made in reality
  • We have not gotten a distribution of ratings by genre with this dataset
  • We possibly have gotten a distribution of ratings by job occupation, but the plot is too difficult for me to decipher, personally. Perhaps artists tend to rate more highly and healthcare workers rate more poorly, but I'm not savy enough with these plots to make that statement.
  • Age is positively associated with higher movie ratings
  • We have not gotten a nice time series visual of movie release dates and ratings. While there are some insights that can be derived from it, such as higher density in more recent years and more variation in ratings in recent years, it's really too messy for me to want to show this to anyone other than myself.
